<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-461-990  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 461 990.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 22 1990 v7 n20 p49(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software 2000 takes wraps off PC-based query tool. (Software 2000introduces Vital Signs 2000 SQL database tool) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Software 2000 Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Vital Signs 2000 (Computer program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Data base management systemsQuery ProcessingStructured Query LanguageProduct IntroductionMicro-Minicomputer CommunicationSearching.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Long known for its financial and human-resources applications for IBMmidrange computers, Software 2000 Inc. earlier this month released its firstPC-based product -- a Structured Query Language (SQL) tool that gives usersaccess to databases running on PCs and larger platforms, company officialssaid.andM;Known as Vital Signs 2000, the software is based on Forest andamp; Trees, anexecutive information system that was developed by Channel Computing Inc. ofNewmarket, N.H.andM;Software 2000 has customized Forest andamp; Trees to serve as a PC front end forits IBM AS/400-based databases covering human resources, financial managementand environmental management, according to Jim Reynolds, marketing managerfor the company, which is located in Hyannis, Mass.andM;The company also provides interfaces that allow Vital Signs 2000 to accessdata stored in other PC or mainframe applications, including SQL Server,dBASE, R:base, Lotus 1-2-3, Paradox, DataEase, Oracle, SQLBase, DB2 and ASCIIflat files.andM;The Forest andamp; Trees front end gives managers &quot;a control panel for running abusiness,&quot; said Jeffrey Tarter, editor of Soft -- Letter, an industrynewsletter published in Watertown, Mass.andM;&quot;It provides a lot of key indicators that people who run businesses need andreally have a tough time getting out of their databases.&quot;andM;Despite its benefits, however, the user interface is rather primitive, Tarternoted.andP;  &quot;It could use a good graphical interface that displays data asobjects on the screen, such as meters, dials or flashing lights,&quot; he said.andM;Software 2000 plans to release a Windows 3.0 version of Vital Signs 2000 inthe third quarter of this year, Reynolds said.andP;  The current version, for DOS3.1 or later, costs from $2,500 to $15,000, depending on systemconfiguration.andM;Software 2000 Inc. can be contacted at (508) 778-2000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>